          <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <!-- SECTION 1: How Does Proprietary Trading Work? -->
          <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <h2 id="how-does-proprietary-trading-work">How Does Proprietary Trading Work?</h2>

          <p>Prop trading works by letting you access firm capital after you prove you can trade profitably within strict risk limits.</p>

          <p>In practice, this usually starts with an evaluation account. You're given virtual funds, real market prices, and a set of rules that decide whether you qualify. Typical targets sit around 8–10%, while maximum drawdown might be 5–10%.</p>

          <div class="not-prose rounded-xl border-l-4 border-amber-400 bg-amber-50/60 px-5 py-4 my-6">
            <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-amber-800 mb-1">From Experience</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">One of the first lessons you learn is that prop drawdown isn't the same as being "down on the week." I've seen accounts fail while still net profitable because one session exceeded the daily loss limit. Two normal-sized losing trades on a slow day can be enough if you're not tracking intraday risk properly.</p>
          </div>

          <p>Once you pass, the funded account looks similar, but the pressure changes. Now the goal isn't passing. It's staying funded long enough to get consistent payouts.</p>


          <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
