          <h3>Traditional Prop Trading Desks</h3>

          <p>Traditional prop desks involve working directly for a firm, usually in an office trading environment.</p>

          <p>Risk is often managed internally, and capital is scaled slowly. You're monitored over time, not over a single evaluation window. Mistakes are corrected through feedback, not instant account closure.</p>

          <p>For most retail traders, this model isn't accessible. It requires location, interviews, and often a finance background.</p>

          <h3>Online Prop Trading Firms</h3>

          <p>Online prop trading firms replace interviews and mentorship with rules and automation.</p>

          <p>This is where most proprietary traders enter the space today. You trade remotely, pass an evaluation, and manage your account independently. You get access to a range of financial instruments (which is obviously firm dependent), but that freedom comes with trade-offs.</p>

          <div class="not-prose rounded-xl border-l-4 border-amber-400 bg-amber-50/60 px-5 py-4 my-6">
            <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-amber-800 mb-1">From Experience</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">One mistake I made early on was moving straight from my first passed challenge into an instant funding account without adjusting my risk. The rules were tighter, the drawdown was trailing, and I hadn't changed how I sized trades. A small pullback wiped out weeks of progress.</p>
          </div>

          <p>Another thing you only learn by experience is how rules are enforced. Some limits are automatic while others are manual. I've had trades that looked fine on the chart, only to be flagged days later because they breached a news rule that wasn't clearly surfaced on the platform.</p>

          <p>That's why reading the rules once isn't enough — you really need to understand how they're applied, not just how they're written. Online prop trading rewards traders who adapt their execution to the rule set. It punishes traders who assume profitability alone is enough.</p>

          <h3>Proprietary Trading at Banks and Financial Institutions</h3>

          <p>Proprietary trading originally developed inside large financial institutions, where investment banks and commercial banks used their own capital to trade financial markets for profit rather than executing trades for clients. These firms ran dedicated proprietary trading desks, staffed by professional traders taking positions across equities, bonds, currencies, commodities, and derivatives.</p>

          <p>In this model, traders were employees trading the firm's own funds, not client funds. Unlike brokerage firms that process trades for customers, proprietary trading desks existed purely to generate profits for the institution, with risk management, position sizing, and losses handled internally.</p>

          <p>While some institutional prop trading still exists today, most retail traders now encounter proprietary trading through independent prop trading firms rather than bank-run trading desks.</p>

          <h3>What's the Difference Between Prop Trading and Hedge Funds?</h3>

          <p>Prop trading and hedge funds are often confused, but the core difference is whose money is being traded. Proprietary trading firms use their own capital, while hedge funds invest client funds raised from outside investors.</p>

          <p>In prop trading, the firm takes the financial risk and shares profits with traders through a split. In hedge funds, profits and losses directly affect investors, with managers paid via management and performance fees. As a result, prop trading focuses more on execution and risk control, while hedge funds operate under investor mandates and longer-term portfolio strategies.</p>


          <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <!-- SECTION 3: Who Is Prop Trading For? -->
          <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <h2 id="who-is-prop-trading-for">Who Is Prop Trading For?</h2>

          <p>Prop trading is best suited to traders who already have a repeatable strategy and can follow risk rules even when emotions kick in.</p>

          <p>If you're still changing systems every few weeks or relying on instinct more than rules, prop trading will feel frustrating fast. When I first moved into prop trading, my strategy was profitable, but my execution wasn't built for fixed drawdown limits. A setup that worked fine on my own account suddenly became a problem when a small losing streak counted against a daily loss cap.</p>

          <p>You tend to do better in prop trading if you already know your numbers. That means knowing how much you risk per trade, how many losses in a row your strategy can handle, and when it makes sense to stop trading for the day.</p>

          <p>Most retail traders enter prop trading through online prop firms rather than traditional desks. That accessibility is a big reason prop trading has grown so quickly, but it also means you're managing everything yourself. There's no risk manager stepping in before you breach a rule. Once you cross the line, the account is usually gone.</p>

          <h3>What I Found Works Well in Prop Trading</h3>

          <p>Before looking at the upsides, it helps to understand the type of trader prop firms are built for. From experience, the following traits matter more than raw win rate.</p>

          <div class="not-prose space-y-2 my-6">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
              <span class="flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5 w-5 h-5 rounded-full bg-teal-500 flex items-center justify-center">
                <svg class="h-3 w-3 text-white" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg>
              </span>
              <span class="text-sm text-slate-700">You're comfortable trading smaller size relative to account balance</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
              <span class="flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5 w-5 h-5 rounded-full bg-teal-500 flex items-center justify-center">
                <svg class="h-3 w-3 text-white" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg>
              </span>
              <span class="text-sm text-slate-700">You're willing to stop trading after hitting a daily loss or profit limit</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
              <span class="flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5 w-5 h-5 rounded-full bg-teal-500 flex items-center justify-center">
                <svg class="h-3 w-3 text-white" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg>
              </span>
              <span class="text-sm text-slate-700">You already track performance — not just PnL but drawdown and expectancy</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-2.5">
              <span class="flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5 w-5 h-5 rounded-full bg-teal-500 flex items-center justify-center">
                <svg class="h-3 w-3 text-white" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg>
              </span>
              <span class="text-sm text-slate-700">You can trade the same setup repeatedly without forcing trades</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>This is why many profitable retail traders still struggle with prop accounts at first. The environment rewards consistency more than aggression.</p>

          <h3>Where Online Prop Trading Makes Sense</h3>

          <p>Online prop trading is often a better fit if you're under-capitalised but already disciplined.</p>

          <div class="not-prose rounded-xl border-l-4 border-amber-400 bg-amber-50/60 px-5 py-4 my-6">
            <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-amber-800 mb-1">From Experience</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">When I passed my first evaluation, the temptation was to immediately scale up to a larger or instant funding account. That's where I ran into trouble. The rules were tighter, the drawdown was trailing, and I hadn't adjusted my position sizing. The strategy didn't fail, but the risk model did.</p>
          </div>

          <p>Online prop trading works best when you treat it like a risk framework first and a profit opportunity second.</p>


          <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <!-- SECTION 4: Pros and Cons of Prop Trading -->
          <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <h2 id="pros-and-cons-of-prop-trading">Pros and Cons of Prop Trading</h2>

          <p>Online prop trading comes with clear trade-offs, and it's worth understanding how they show up in real trading before committing.</p>

          <!-- Summary pros/cons grid -->
          <div class="not-prose grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 my-8">
            <div class="rounded-2xl border border-teal-200 bg-teal-50/30 p-5">
