                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-slate-700">
                  <svg class="mt-0.5 h-4 w-4 flex-shrink-0 text-teal-500" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M16.707 5.293a1 1 0 010 1.414l-8 8a1 1 0 01-1.414 0l-4-4a1 1 0 011.414-1.414L8 12.586l7.293-7.293a1 1 0 011.414 0z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
                  Main upfront cost is the challenge fee
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-slate-700">
                  <svg class="mt-0.5 h-4 w-4 flex-shrink-0 text-teal-500" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M16.707 5.293a1 1 0 010 1.414l-8 8a1 1 0 01-1.414 0l-4-4a1 1 0 011.414-1.414L8 12.586l7.293-7.293a1 1 0 011.414 0z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
                  Scaling can let you grow your account sizes
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-slate-700">
                  <svg class="mt-0.5 h-4 w-4 flex-shrink-0 text-teal-500" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M16.707 5.293a1 1 0 010 1.414l-8 8a1 1 0 01-1.414 0l-4-4a1 1 0 011.414-1.414L8 12.586l7.293-7.293a1 1 0 011.414 0z" clip-rule="evenodd"/></svg>
                  Profit splits can be as high as 90%, even 100%
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="rounded-2xl border border-red-200 bg-red-50/30 p-5">
              <p class="text-xs font-black uppercase tracking-widest text-red-500 mb-4">Cons</p>
              <ul class="space-y-2.5">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-slate-700">
                  <svg class="mt-0.5 h-4 w-4 flex-shrink-0 text-red-400" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M6 18L18 6M6 6l12 12"/></svg>
                  Evaluation process can be hard to pass
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-slate-700">
                  <svg class="mt-0.5 h-4 w-4 flex-shrink-0 text-red-400" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M6 18L18 6M6 6l12 12"/></svg>
                  Trading rules can be complex
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-slate-700">
                  <svg class="mt-0.5 h-4 w-4 flex-shrink-0 text-red-400" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M6 18L18 6M6 6l12 12"/></svg>
                  Discipline is required to pass challenges
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-slate-700">
                  <svg class="mt-0.5 h-4 w-4 flex-shrink-0 text-red-400" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M6 18L18 6M6 6l12 12"/></svg>
                  Not regulated like CFD and forex brokers
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>Before I explain each point in detail, it's worth understanding that these pros and cons don't exist in isolation. Most traders experience several of them at the same time, often within their first few challenges. How these factors play out depends less on the firm's marketing and more on how you trade, manage risk, and adapt to structure.</p>

          <!-- Pro 1 -->
          <h3>
            <span class="not-prose inline-flex items-center justify-center w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-teal-500 text-white text-xs font-black mr-2 align-middle">1</span>
            Pro — Access to Larger Amounts of Capital
          </h3>

          <p>Access to larger capital is the obvious attraction, but it changes how you trade more than most people expect.</p>

          <p>When you first move from a small personal account to a prop account, the temptation is to trade bigger because the balance looks bigger. What actually worked better was doing the opposite. I ended up risking less per trade than I ever had before, sometimes 0.25% or less. The edge wasn't size — it was being able to trade clean setups without feeling rushed to make money quickly. The capital gives you room to breathe, but only if you respect it.</p>

          <!-- Pro 2 -->
          <h3>
            <span class="not-prose inline-flex items-center justify-center w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-teal-500 text-white text-xs font-black mr-2 align-middle">2</span>
            Pro — Main Upfront Cost Is the Challenge Fee
          </h3>

          <p>The challenge fee feels small compared to the account size you're trading, and although this is a major perk, it can create bad habits early.</p>

          <p>When I first started, I treated challenge fees like disposable attempts. If a day went badly, I'd push harder instead of stepping away because "it's only the fee." That mindset led to more failed challenges than bad trading ever did. Once you treat the evaluation like a real account, your decision making changes. The fee stops feeling cheap once you've paid it a few times.</p>

          <!-- Pro 3 -->
          <h3>
            <span class="not-prose inline-flex items-center justify-center w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-teal-500 text-white text-xs font-black mr-2 align-middle">3</span>
            Pro — Scaling Can Let You Grow Your Account Sizes
          </h3>

          <p>Scaling is one of the most underrated benefits of prop trading when it works well.</p>

          <p>Once you've proven consistency, scaling lets you increase account size without starting from scratch. When this clicked for me, the biggest advantage wasn't earning more per trade — it was being able to keep the same risk model while letting the account do more of the work. The strategy didn't change. The execution didn't change. The capital did.</p>

          <p>If your entries are clean and your risk is already controlled, scaling feels natural. You're not forced to trade more often or take lower-quality setups. You're simply applying the same process to a larger base, which is exactly what most traders are trying to do long term.</p>

          <!-- Pro 4 -->
          <h3>
            <span class="not-prose inline-flex items-center justify-center w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-teal-500 text-white text-xs font-black mr-2 align-middle">4</span>
            Pro — Profit Splits Can Be as High as 90%, Even 100%
          </h3>

          <p>High profit splits are one of the clearest advantages of trading with a prop firm.</p>

          <p>Once you're funded and taking regular payouts, the split becomes very real very quickly. When I started receiving consistent payouts, the difference between an 80% and 90% split wasn't theoretical anymore. Over a few months, it materially changed what I took home, even though the trading stayed the same.</p>

          <p>What makes this powerful is that you're earning that percentage on capital you didn't have to build yourself. When things are running smoothly, it lets you think in terms of monthly performance and withdrawals rather than individual wins and losses — which is where prop trading starts to feel like a proper trading framework rather than a challenge grind.</p>

          <!-- Con 5 -->
          <h3>
            <span class="not-prose inline-flex items-center justify-center w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-red-400 text-white text-xs font-black mr-2 align-middle">5</span>
            Con — Prop Challenges Can Be Hard to Pass
          </h3>

          <p>Most traders underestimate how demanding prop challenges actually are. I did when I started. My early failures weren't about bad strategies — instead they came from the structure of the challenge itself. You're usually trying to make 8–10% while working inside a relatively tight drawdown, and that imbalance changes how every trade feels. A couple of normal losses or too wide a stop can suddenly put you on the back foot, even if your edge is sound.</p>

          <p>What makes this harder is the time pressure. You're trading knowing there's a target to hit, which pushes many traders to overtrade, size up, or take setups they'd normally skip. Passing challenges ended up being less about finding great trades and more about managing yourself when nothing clean was setting up. That's where most accounts are lost.</p>

          <!-- Con 6 -->
          <h3>
            <span class="not-prose inline-flex items-center justify-center w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-red-400 text-white text-xs font-black mr-2 align-middle">6</span>
            Con — Trading Rules Can Be Complex
          </h3>

          <p>Prop firm rules often seem clear and easy to understand, until you trade under them. Some firms enforce almost everything automatically, so you'll see violations instantly. Others use a mix of automatic and manual checks, and a few rely heavily on post-trade reviews. I've traded with firms where nothing flagged in real time, only to be notified days later that a rule had been breached. By then, the trade was long closed and the damage was already done.</p>

          <p>Another thing that catches people up is that rules often change between the challenge and the funded account. A strategy that's allowed during evaluation may have tighter limits once you're funded, especially around news trading, automation, or holding positions. Some firms also charge add-on fees for things like trading during news or using automated strategies, which isn't always obvious upfront.</p>

          <p>If you don't understand how rules are enforced — whether they're automatic or manual, and whether they differ between challenge and funded accounts — you're trading with gaps in your information. That's usually where unexpected violations come from, not bad trades.</p>

          <!-- Con 7 -->
          <h3>
            <span class="not-prose inline-flex items-center justify-center w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-red-400 text-white text-xs font-black mr-2 align-middle">7</span>
            Con — Discipline Is Required to Pass Challenges
          </h3>

          <p>Prop trading punishes emotional trading far more than retail trading. Any habit you already have gets magnified. Overtrading after a win, revenge trading after a loss, or forcing trades on slow days — all lead to the same outcome. I passed more challenges by trading less, not more. Flat days became acceptable. Missing trades became normal. Discipline wasn't about being perfect — it was about not doing damage.</p>

          <!-- Con 8 -->
          <h3>
            <span class="not-prose inline-flex items-center justify-center w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-red-400 text-white text-xs font-black mr-2 align-middle">8</span>
            Con — Not Regulated Like CFD and Forex Brokers
          </h3>

          <p>Prop firms aren't regulated in the same way as brokers, and that matters. You're trading in a simulated environment, and the protections you're used to with brokers don't always apply. Two firms can advertise similar rules but handle disputes, payouts, and violations very differently. I learned quickly that reputation and transparency matter more than headline offers. This isn't something to gloss over, especially once real payouts are involved.</p>


          <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <!-- SECTION 5: Understanding the Risks -->
          <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <h2 id="understanding-the-risks">Understanding the Risks of Prop Trading Before You Start</h2>

          <p>Prop trading still carries real risk, even though you're not trading your own capital.</p>

          <div class="not-prose rounded-xl border-l-4 border-red-400 bg-red-50/60 px-5 py-4 my-6">
            <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-red-700 mb-1">Risk Warning</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">Most evaluations require you to make around 8–10% while staying within a 5% or similar drawdown. That imbalance means risk management has to be tighter than most retail traders are used to. One poorly managed session can undo weeks of steady gains.</p>
          </div>

          <p>Digital prop firms also vary widely in how they operate. Two firms can advertise almost identical rules and produce very different outcomes once you're trading. That's why research matters, especially around enforcement, payouts, and account management.</p>

          <p>If you go into prop trading expecting flexibility, you'll struggle. If you go in expecting structure, constraints, and repetition, you're approaching it with the right mindset.</p>


          <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <!-- SECTION 6: Common Proprietary Trading Strategies -->
          <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <h2 id="common-proprietary-trading-strategies">Common Proprietary Trading Strategies</h2>

          <p>In prop trading, your strategy is whatever survives the firm's rules. When I first moved into funded accounts, I didn't change my edge, but I had to acknowledge that daily loss limits, trailing drawdown, and holding rules decide what's actually tradable.</p>

          <p>Most of what works is execution-based. I ended up leaning on short-term price action, tight intraday momentum, and simple swing setups around clear levels — because I could control risk precisely. Anything that needed wide stops or patience over multiple days kept running into drawdown limits.</p>

          <p>The biggest adjustment was realising strategies aren't universal. A setup that worked fine at one prop firm failed at another because the drawdown model was different. That's when it clicked that prop trading isn't about finding the best strategy. It's about adapting a simple one to the specific rules of the firm you're trading with and executing it the same way every day.</p>


          <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <!-- SECTION 7: Are Prop Firms Regulated? -->
          <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <h2 id="are-prop-firms-regulated">Are Prop Firms Regulated?</h2>

          <p>No, prop firms aren't regulated like forex and CFD brokers. Recently the industry has faced more scrutiny, but because most prop traders operate in a simulated trading environment, it's a grey area for financial regulators.</p>

          <p>There are some regions trying to manage things, with countries like Australia setting limitations on funded trader programs and introducing augmented reporting obligations for forex brokers pivoting into the prop trading space.</p>

          <p>Regardless of these constraints, there's only so much financial authorities like ASIC in Australia or the FCA in the UK can enforce, as unlike brokerage operations, prop firms aren't deposit-taking companies, and evaluations operate in a simulated environment that mirrors real market conditions.</p>


          <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <!-- SECTION 8: Quick History of Prop Trading -->
          <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <h2 id="quick-history-of-prop-trading">Quick History of Prop Trading</h2>

          <p>Proprietary trading has roots going back decades. It originally existed inside investment banks and large financial institutions where dedicated desks traded the firm's own capital across equities, bonds, currencies, and derivatives. Traders were employees, and risk was managed internally.</p>

          <p>The landscape changed significantly after the 2008 financial crisis. Regulations like the Volcker Rule in the United States restricted banks from engaging in proprietary trading, pushing the practice outside traditional financial institutions.</p>

          <p>This created space for independent prop trading firms to emerge — first as in-person operations, then increasingly as online platforms accessible to retail traders worldwide. Today, online prop firms dominate the space, offering remote evaluations and funded accounts to traders in virtually every country.</p>


          <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <!-- SECTION 9: FAQs -->
          <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
          <h2 id="faqs">FAQs</h2>
        </div>

        <!-- FAQ cards (outside prose for custom styling) -->
        <div class="space-y-4 mt-6">
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-bold text-sm text-slate-900 mb-2">Is prop trading illegal?</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Prop trading is not illegal, but it operates differently from traditional regulated trading and forex brokers. When you trade with a prop firm, you're trading the firm's capital, usually in a simulated environment, rather than trading client funds like a broker does. That's why prop firms aren't regulated in the same way as CFD or forex brokers — because they aren't deposit-taking entities and you aren't trading in live markets. Legality can also depend on your country and how the firm structures its challenges, so it's important to understand the rules and requirements before signing up.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-bold text-sm text-slate-900 mb-2">How do prop traders get paid?</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Prop traders get paid through profit splits on funded accounts after meeting the firm's payout conditions. Once you're funded, profits are split between you and the firm, usually on a weekly or monthly schedule depending on the provider. Typical splits range from 70% to 90%, with some firms offering higher under specific conditions. Staying funded is just as important as being profitable.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-bold text-sm text-slate-900 mb-2">Do prop traders make good money?</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Some prop traders make good money, but income varies widely and depends on consistency, not just strategy. Earnings depend on how long you keep your funded account, the size of your account and whether scaling plans are available, the profit split, and how often you withdraw funds. Many traders fail before reaching regular profit payouts, while others build steady monthly income over time. Prop trading rewards disciplined traders who manage risk well, rather than those chasing big wins or fast results.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-bold text-sm text-slate-900 mb-2">How do I become a prop trader?</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">You become a prop trader by passing a firm's evaluation and qualifying for a funded account. You start by choosing an online prop firm, paying a challenge fee, and trading a simulated account under set rules. If you hit the profit target without breaching drawdown or risk limits, you're offered a funded account. From there, the focus shifts from passing challenges to staying funded and managing payouts consistently.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

      </article>
    </div>
